which turned into a fever...

739
00:59:43,632 --> 00:59:47,159
...which turned into inflammation
of my brain and spinal cord.

740
00:59:47,335 --> 00:59:49,269
It's called encephalomyelitis.

741
00:59:49,437 --> 00:59:53,965
And they had to operate,
in the back, here.

742
00:59:54,142 --> 00:59:59,910
It was a complicated procedure. It was
eight hours. And they nearly lost me.

743
01:00:00,082 --> 01:00:03,916
Actually, technically, they did lose me...

744
01:00:04,086 --> 01:00:07,078
...and bring me back
on a number of occasions.

745
01:00:08,591 --> 01:00:10,183
Anyway, they cured the illness...

746
01:00:10,359 --> 01:00:15,194
...but they must've messed up something
else while they were back there, because...

747
01:00:15,364 --> 01:00:17,992
...not long after,
I started to have these migraines.

748
01:00:18,167 --> 01:00:20,727
And then nightmares.

749
01:00:20,903 --> 01:00:26,000
And then these connections.

750
01:00:27,743 --> 01:00:32,476
And one day I'm sitting with a friend,
and I had a vision of a woman...

751
01:00:32,648 --> 01:00:34,309
...a crystal-clear vision.

752
01:00:34,483 --> 01:00:36,951
And I described her to him.

753
01:00:37,119 --> 01:00:42,318
And turned out it was an exact description
of his mother, someone I'd never met...

754
01:00:42,491 --> 01:00:46,689
...who'd died the previous week.

755
01:00:48,664 --> 01:00:50,495
And you're not laughing yet.

756
01:00:50,666 --> 01:00:52,258
No, I'm not.

757
01:00:54,270 --> 01:00:57,000
Well, anyway, I assumed
it was some kind of a coincidence.

758
01:00:57,173 --> 01:01:02,509
But as time went on, I began having more
and more of these things, connections.

759
01:01:03,714 --> 01:01:06,877
So the doctors ran a bunch of tests.

760
01:01:07,050 --> 01:01:10,747
They told my parents that I'd developed
something called passive schizophrenia.

761
01:01:10,921 --> 01:01:15,051
They gave me a bunch of pills and,
you know, the pills stopped the visions...

762
01:01:15,225 --> 01:01:18,217
...but they pretty much
stopped everything else also...

763
01:01:18,395 --> 01:01:20,056
...so I had this choice.

764
01:01:20,230 --> 01:01:24,223
I was either gonna live my life
with these hallucinations...

765
01:01:24,401 --> 01:01:26,801
...with apparently no way
of switching it off.

766
01:01:27,971 --> 01:01:30,804
Or I could have no life at all.

767
01:01:30,974 --> 01:01:32,771
Oh, my God.

768
01:01:32,943 --> 01:01:37,141
See, there, now I've been
neglecting my duties.

769
01:01:38,081 --> 01:01:42,177
Could I ask you a question?

770
01:01:43,954 --> 01:01:46,047
You know, these are probably
ready to go in.

771
01:01:46,223 --> 01:01:47,781
George?

772
01:01:52,696 --> 01:01:55,096
Would it be okay if I told you
the answer was no?

773
01:01:55,265 --> 01:01:57,460
You don't even know
what I was gonna ask.

774
01:01:57,635 --> 01:02:01,093
Yes, I do. You're gonna ask me
if I can do a reading for you.

775
01:02:02,974 --> 01:02:06,137
Look, Melanie, I barely know you...

776
01:02:06,310 --> 01:02:08,904
...but I like you a lot.

777
01:02:09,080 --> 01:02:10,809
Really, a lot.

778
01:02:11,649 --> 01:02:14,846
Is there any way we could pretend
that maybe we go back in time...

779
01:02:15,019 --> 01:02:19,353
...and just forget about the phone ringing,
and my brother's message...

780
01:02:19,524 --> 01:02:21,992
- ...and we never had this conversation?
- Why?

781
01:02:22,160 --> 01:02:24,151
If we open the door
and go down that road...

782
01:02:24,662 --> 01:02:30,123
...any chance that we had of having
something normal will just be gone.

783
01:02:30,935 --> 01:02:32,095
It just will.

784
01:02:32,270 --> 01:02:36,036
Believe me. I have enough
experience of that now.

785
01:02:37,508 --> 01:02:40,204
I mean, sometimes, I mean....

786
01:02:40,378 --> 01:02:44,041
You know, knowing everything
about someone, it's--

787
01:02:44,215 --> 01:02:46,979
You know, it seems nice, but, really...

788
01:02:47,151 --> 01:02:50,609
...maybe it's actually better
to hold stuff back.

789
01:02:50,788 --> 01:02:52,756
I hear you.

790
01:02:52,924 --> 01:02:57,190
But you can understand. I'm curious.

791
01:02:57,361 --> 01:03:00,819
No, of course. I mean, yeah. Yeah.

792
01:03:01,967 --> 01:03:03,764
Please?

793
01:03:07,473 --> 01:03:08,565
[WHOOSH]

794
01:03:19,351 --> 01:03:20,750
Okay.

795
01:03:22,588 --> 01:03:23,885
Come on.

796
01:03:29,495 --> 01:03:31,429
Here, take a seat.

797
01:03:31,697 --> 01:03:33,358
MELANIE:
Okay.

798
01:03:35,801 --> 01:03:38,736
I'm gonna take your hands for a second,
to get a connection...

799
01:03:38,904 --> 01:03:42,169
...and then I'll let go, and I'll just
ask you a couple questions.

800
01:03:42,341 --> 01:03:43,399
All right.

801
01:03:43,575 --> 01:03:44,906
Okay. Give me your hands.

802
01:03:45,911 --> 01:03:47,276
Okay.

803
01:03:49,414 --> 01:03:50,608
[WHOOSH]

804
01:03:54,720 --> 01:03:56,051
Okay.

805
01:03:58,825 --> 01:04:02,488
There's a woman. And she's tall.

806
01:04:03,062 --> 01:04:06,054
Thin. She has brown hair.

807
01:04:07,734 --> 01:04:09,929
Do you know who I'm talking about?

808
01:04:13,106 --> 01:04:14,573
Is this woman your mother?

809
01:04:16,643 --> 01:04:18,201
Yes.

810
01:04:19,712 --> 01:04:21,942
And I'm feeling a pain in my chest.

811
01:04:25,485 --> 01:04:30,616
Yeah. That's how she died.
Of a heart attack.

812
01:04:30,790 --> 01:04:32,155
I'm sorry.

813
01:04:35,628 --> 01:04:37,095
Okay. You ready to eat?

814
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:43,093
There's not something else?

815
01:04:43,269 --> 01:04:46,670
- No, there's nothing--
- No, no, no, I can tell.

816
01:04:46,839 --> 01:04:49,672
Please, there is, I can tell.

817
01:04:50,743 --> 01:04:54,804
I mean, what's the matter?
You don't think I could handle it?

818
01:04:58,319 --> 01:05:00,549
All right, um....

819
01:05:02,656 --> 01:05:05,022
When you touched me before,
there was a....

820
01:05:05,659 --> 01:05:07,422
There was a man.

821
01:05:08,796 --> 01:05:10,161
Dark hair.

822
01:05:15,936 --> 01:05:17,665
My father.

823
01:05:17,838 --> 01:05:19,533
He passed away not too long ago?

824
01:05:20,774 --> 01:05:23,140
- Last year.
- And....

825
01:05:24,411 --> 01:05:27,847
All he kept saying,
all I kept hearing was--

826
01:05:28,015 --> 01:05:29,107
Was what?

827
01:05:32,820 --> 01:05:34,219
How sorry he was.

828
01:05:36,724 --> 01:05:38,157
What for?

829
01:05:38,325 --> 01:05:41,988
For what he did to you all that time ago.

830
01:05:45,532 --> 01:05:51,493
And he hoped
that you could one day forgive him.

831
01:05:55,242 --> 01:05:56,573
I'm sorry.

832
01:06:01,850 --> 01:06:03,545
I'm sorry.

833
01:06:05,453 --> 01:06:07,683
I'm sorry...

834
01:06:10,959 --> 01:06:13,189
...for pressing you like that.

835
01:06:16,865 --> 01:06:21,199
Maybe we shouldn't have gone there.

836
01:06:23,672 --> 01:06:25,663
I don't know what to say.

837
01:06:31,846 --> 01:06:33,973
Except if I....

838
01:06:34,149 --> 01:06:37,550
If I go now...

839
01:06:38,620 --> 01:06:42,181
...if we draw a line under this...

840
01:06:42,590 --> 01:06:45,081
...pretend it never happened...

841
01:06:51,232 --> 01:06:52,927
...we'll be okay.

842
01:06:54,269 --> 01:06:55,497
I'm sure.

843
01:06:56,404 --> 01:06:57,769
Good.

844
01:06:59,775 --> 01:07:01,208
Good.

845
01:07:12,254 --> 01:07:15,815
We still have the competition
to win. Right?

846
01:07:16,258 --> 01:07:17,623
Right.

847
01:07:19,395 --> 01:07:21,955
I should've listened to you.

848
01:07:22,131 --> 01:07:25,464
You know, too much knowledge
and all that.

849
01:07:35,077 --> 01:07:36,772
I'll see you next week.

850
01:07:36,946 --> 01:07:38,470
Yeah, you betcha.

851
01:08:00,270 --> 01:08:02,261
[SOBBING]

852
01:08:47,417 --> 01:08:51,581
MAN [OVER SPEAKERS] The old, unhappy
feeling that had once pervaded my life...

853
01:08:51,755 --> 01:08:57,990
...came back like an unwelcome visitor,
and deeper than ever.

854
01:08:58,161 --> 01:09:02,359
It addressed me like a strain
of sorrowful music...

855
01:09:02,533 --> 01:09:06,902
...a hopeless consciousness
of all that I had lost...

856
01:09:07,071 --> 01:09:09,835
...all that I had ever loved.

857
01:09:10,007 --> 01:09:15,536
And all that remained
was a ruined blank and waste...

858
01:09:15,713 --> 01:09:21,208
...lying around me,
unbroken to the dark horizon.

859
01:09:23,354 --> 01:09:25,151
CLARE:
All right, son, out you get.

860
01:09:26,390 --> 01:09:30,087
All right. Lovely, thanks.

861
01:09:32,029 --> 01:09:34,725
- Hello.
ANGELA & DENNIS: Hi, Marcus!

862
01:09:34,966 --> 01:09:37,434
Hi. I'm Angela. This is Dennis.

863
01:09:37,602 --> 01:09:39,160
DENNIS:
All right, mate?

864
01:09:39,737 --> 01:09:41,068
ANGELA:
I call him Dennis the Menace.

865
01:09:41,239 --> 01:09:42,706
[DENNIS & ANGELA CHUCKLE]

866
01:09:42,874 --> 01:09:46,173
Now, I'll show you the kitchen.

867
01:09:46,744 --> 01:09:48,905
Just keep walking through there.

868
01:09:49,380 --> 01:09:52,440
So this is where we eat
our breakfast in the morning.

869
01:09:52,617 --> 01:09:55,017
What do you like to eat in the mornings?

870
01:09:55,753 --> 01:09:58,847
We're porridge eaters in this house.
Do you like porridge?

871
01:10:00,959 --> 01:10:02,620
Or cornflakes?

872
01:10:13,005 --> 01:10:14,472
DENNIS:
This is your room.

873
01:10:17,309 --> 01:10:20,403
Our last boy, Ricky, moved out
about a month ago.

874
01:10:20,579 --> 01:10:24,538
Just turned 18.
Got his first job, security guard.

875
01:10:26,084 --> 01:10:28,245
Go on, mate. It's all yours now.

876
01:10:31,323 --> 01:10:33,848
SOCIAL WORKER [WHISPERS]: Do you
think it's possible to get another bed?

877
01:10:36,028 --> 01:10:37,620
Two secs, Marcus.

878
01:10:38,964 --> 01:10:40,761
DENNIS [WHISPERS]:
We're gonna need another bed.

879
01:10:41,333 --> 01:10:43,597
Upstairs? Should I take yours?

880
01:10:53,378 --> 01:10:55,005
DENNIS: You all right?
- Yeah.

881
01:11:42,829 --> 01:11:44,421
Good night, Jase.

882
01:11:47,367 --> 01:11:51,064
Who agrees? A and D. "Rowan is an
old Roman word for a mountain ash."

883
01:11:51,237 --> 01:11:53,000
"A mountain ash lives over 100 years."

884
01:11:53,172 --> 01:11:56,073
And does anybody else
think it's anything else?

885
01:11:56,242 --> 01:11:59,177
Marcus, could you take
the hat off, please?

886
01:12:00,547 --> 01:12:01,605
Thank you.

887
01:12:01,815 --> 01:12:05,012
So now let's move on to number six.

888
01:12:05,185 --> 01:12:06,447
On the next page.

889
01:12:06,620 --> 01:12:11,683
So you're gonna need to look
at the extract, "Wings of Courage."

890
01:12:18,065 --> 01:12:20,533
- Thank you very much for coming in.
- You're welcome.

891
01:12:20,701 --> 01:12:22,328
And....

892
01:12:22,503 --> 01:12:24,266
SOCIAL WORKER: We'll be in touch
when we've made the appointment.

893
01:12:24,438 --> 01:12:25,769
Yeah. Okay, great.

894
01:12:25,939 --> 01:12:27,429
CLARE:
Let's get it sorted as soon as possible.

895
01:12:27,608 --> 01:12:28,632
Thanks.

896
01:12:28,809 --> 01:12:30,902
CLARE:
All right, Marcus? See you soon, mate.

897
01:12:31,078 --> 01:12:32,978
SOCIAL WORKER:
Be a good little man.

898
01:12:37,384 --> 01:12:39,375
[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

899
01:12:44,391 --> 01:12:46,757
TEACHER:
It's lunchtime, Marcus. You gonna go?

900
01:13:14,656 --> 01:13:17,454
[ON COMPUTER]
The angel of death comes to you...

901
01:13:18,293 --> 01:13:22,059
...and will find you,
no matter where you are hiding.

902
01:13:22,230 --> 01:13:26,599
Even if you are hiding in,
like a rich man in a castle...

903
01:13:27,268 --> 01:13:31,068
...the angel of God will find you.

904
01:13:32,507 --> 01:13:34,168
[SINGING IN ARABIC]

905
01:13:39,614 --> 01:13:41,445
Hello.

906
01:13:41,616 --> 01:13:44,414
A number of us are probably
too frightened to ask:

907
01:13:44,586 --> 01:13:46,213
"What happens to us when we die?"

908
01:13:47,455 --> 01:13:52,483
But the good news is, if you believe
in Christ, you have nothing to fear.

909
01:14:41,410 --> 01:14:43,002
[RECEPTIONIST SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

910
01:14:43,179 --> 01:14:45,170
[MARIE SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

911
01:14:46,081 --> 01:14:48,072
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

912
01:15:09,973 --> 01:15:11,964
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

913
01:15:13,910 --> 01:15:15,901
[EKG BEEPING]

914
01:15:31,261 --> 01:15:33,252
[HUSBAND GROANING]

915
01:15:34,164 --> 01:15:36,155
[PATIENT WHEEZES]

916
01:15:46,109 --> 01:15:47,974
[HUSBAND SOBBING]

917
01:16:01,292 --> 01:16:03,283
[HUSBAND SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

918
01:16:04,128 --> 01:16:06,119
[ROUSSEAU SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

919
01:16:07,265 --> 01:16:09,460
[IN ENGLISH]
Excuse me. I don't understand.

920
01:16:09,634 --> 01:16:13,570
Ah. What wouldn't we give to know
exactly where she's gone?

921
01:16:13,738 --> 01:16:17,105
But from what you wrote in your letter,
perhaps you know already.

922
01:16:17,908 --> 01:16:20,069
- Claudia Rousseau.
- Marie Lelay.

923
01:16:20,244 --> 01:16:22,303
- I'm so happy to meet you.
- You too.

924
01:16:22,480 --> 01:16:26,280
You know, I really need to talk
about the vision I had.

925
01:16:27,051 --> 01:16:28,313
- Sure, go ahead.
- Yeah.

926
01:16:28,486 --> 01:16:32,115
It was a very peaceful sensation.

927
01:16:32,590 --> 01:16:37,186
Everything was quiet.
Darkness everywhere.

928
01:16:37,361 --> 01:16:40,421
And a light was catching my eyes.

929
01:16:40,598 --> 01:16:43,123
And I was hearing the sound
of a gentle wind.

930
01:16:43,301 --> 01:16:44,325
ROUSSEAU:
Mm-hm.

931
01:16:45,069 --> 01:16:47,594
A feeling of weightlessness?

932
01:16:47,772 --> 01:16:49,137
Yes.

933
01:16:49,307 --> 01:16:51,832
A 360 perspective?

934
01:16:52,009 --> 01:16:54,705
No sense of linear time or motion?

935
01:16:54,879 --> 01:16:56,141
Yes.

936
01:16:56,314 --> 01:16:58,043
But all-knowing, all-sensing?

937
01:16:58,215 --> 01:16:59,409
Exactly.

938
01:16:59,583 --> 01:17:01,778
- Would you care for some tea?
- Thank you.

939
01:17:01,953 --> 01:17:05,980
You know, as a scientist and atheist...

940
01:17:06,158 --> 01:17:08,922
...my mind was closed to such things.

941
01:17:09,094 --> 01:17:12,723
Oh, absolutely.
Afterlife, near-death experiences.

942
01:17:12,898 --> 01:17:15,833
Like everyone else,
I thought people saw bright lights...

943
01:17:16,001 --> 01:17:17,901
...Eden-like gardens and so forth...

944
01:17:18,103 --> 01:17:21,732
...because they were
culturally conditioned to do so.

945
01:17:21,907 --> 01:17:26,241
But after 25 years in a hospice...

946
01:17:26,411 --> 01:17:29,608
...working with people,
many of whom were pronounced dead...

947
01:17:30,315 --> 01:17:32,977
...but then miraculously survived...

948
01:17:33,151 --> 01:17:37,588
...the account of what they actually
experienced were so strikingly similar...

949
01:17:37,756 --> 01:17:40,156
...it couldn't just be coincidence.

950
01:17:42,227 --> 01:17:45,390
And add to that the fact that when
they had these experiences...

951
01:17:45,564 --> 01:17:47,828
...they were almost all unconscious...

952
01:17:47,999 --> 01:17:53,562
...a state in which my enemies agree
the brain cannot create fresh images.

953
01:17:55,841 --> 01:17:58,776
So you think I really did
experience something?

954
01:17:58,944 --> 01:18:00,241
Oh, yes.

955
01:18:01,881 --> 01:18:03,576
I think you experienced death.

956
01:18:07,286 --> 01:18:09,254
It's all here.

957
01:18:09,422 --> 01:18:13,620
I'm afraid if your journey is anything
like mine, it won't be an easy one.

958
01:18:13,793 --> 01:18:15,624
It's a lonely field to plow.

959
01:18:15,795 --> 01:18:20,027
People get quite irrational around
this subject. Quite hostile, even.

960
01:18:20,199 --> 01:18:23,293
But the evidence is irrefutable.

961
01:18:23,469 --> 01:18:25,164
I tried.

962
01:18:30,309 --> 01:18:32,607
You know, perhaps someone like you...

963
01:18:33,946 --> 01:18:37,541
...in your position, and with your influence,
can change that.

964
01:18:39,085 --> 01:18:40,575
I hope you can.

965
01:18:41,053 --> 01:18:42,680
Thank you.

966
01:18:44,690 --> 01:18:45,952
ROUSSEAU:
Good luck.

967
01:18:46,125 --> 01:18:47,786
I'll send it back when I'm done.

968
01:19:10,517 --> 01:19:12,508
[WOMAN 1 SPEAKING IN FRENCH ON TV]

969
01:19:21,061 --> 01:19:22,392
