976
01:20:15,250 --> 01:20:16,274
Yeah, I heard.

977
01:20:16,851 --> 01:20:20,378
Yeah. Anyway, seems the suits
got together with the unions...

978
01:20:20,555 --> 01:20:24,685
...and came up with packages for anyone
willing to consider voluntary redundancy.

979
01:20:25,159 --> 01:20:26,751
Voluntary redundancy?

980
01:20:26,928 --> 01:20:29,192
Look, if you ask me,
the deal is pretty good.

981
01:20:29,430 --> 01:20:33,526
You get six months' pay in your pocket
with health insurance for two years.

982
01:20:33,701 --> 01:20:36,033
So, what does this have to do with me?

983
01:20:36,604 --> 01:20:37,935
[SIGHS]

984
01:20:42,210 --> 01:20:44,940
BILLY: It's a freaking scandal.
You worked there three years?

985
01:20:45,113 --> 01:20:47,206
You never missed a day,
never called in sick.

986
01:20:47,382 --> 01:20:50,180
- He said it was nothing personal.
- That's B.S.

987
01:20:50,351 --> 01:20:53,013
He's trying to protect the guys
who have wives and kids.

988
01:20:53,187 --> 01:20:55,815
- You should hire a lawyer.
- I can't afford a lawyer.

989
01:20:55,990 --> 01:20:58,982
If you need help getting another job,
I'll help you with that.

990
01:20:59,160 --> 01:21:03,153
I'll make calls. I'll make it happen. But you
know what I think you should do, right?

991
01:21:03,332 --> 01:21:05,061
Yes, I do.

992
01:21:05,234 --> 01:21:09,295
You know, the website's still up.
Waiting.

993
01:21:09,471 --> 01:21:12,065
It'd be different this time, George.

994
01:21:12,942 --> 01:21:16,571
We could control it.
That's how it would be different.

995
01:21:16,745 --> 01:21:19,441
We'd only do two clients a day,
three, tops. Keep it small.

996
01:21:19,615 --> 01:21:22,482
Don't give out your phone number.
We won't talk to the media.

997
01:21:22,651 --> 01:21:25,119
We learned our lesson
with that the last time, right?

998
01:21:27,356 --> 01:21:29,824
Just think about it, all right?

999
01:21:37,399 --> 01:21:39,629
- Doing all right, George?
- Yeah.

1000
01:21:39,802 --> 01:21:41,770
Look a little bummed out.

1001
01:21:41,937 --> 01:21:44,064
Listen, I'll step in and partner with you.

1002
01:21:44,239 --> 01:21:47,140
Me and you could win this thing,
you know?

1003
01:21:47,309 --> 01:21:48,708
- Why not?
GEORGE: Yeah.

1004
01:21:49,445 --> 01:21:50,935
Great.

1005
01:21:51,180 --> 01:21:53,239
Watch your fingers there.

1006
01:22:14,337 --> 01:22:16,328
[RINGING]

1007
01:22:16,773 --> 01:22:18,866
- Hello?
DENNIS [OVER PHONE]: Clare?

1008
01:22:19,042 --> 01:22:21,510
Dennis. I think you should come over.

1009
01:22:22,679 --> 01:22:25,079
Yeah, of course, Dennis. I'll come now.

1010
01:22:27,684 --> 01:22:30,482
SOCIAL WORKER: How much was in here?
DENNIS: Two hundred pounds.

1011
01:22:30,654 --> 01:22:33,555
We called the school. He never got there.

1012
01:22:33,723 --> 01:22:35,520
What happens now?

1013
01:22:35,692 --> 01:22:37,922
Well, we don't want to
involve the police.

1014
01:22:38,094 --> 01:22:40,028
No, that's really a last resort.

1015
01:22:42,032 --> 01:22:44,023
Will you let us know if he comes back?

1016
01:22:44,701 --> 01:22:46,566
SOCIAL WORKER:
We will be in touch.

1017
01:22:48,038 --> 01:22:50,029
I'll see you out.

1018
01:23:01,484 --> 01:23:02,974
MAN 1:
There you go.

1019
01:23:15,499 --> 01:23:18,525
MAN 2: I'm afraid our sensitive,
Mr. Hewitt, is very busy.

1020
01:23:18,703 --> 01:23:21,399
Earliest he could see you
is six weeks' time.

1021
01:23:21,572 --> 01:23:22,937
MAN 3:
Oh, dear.

1022
01:23:23,107 --> 01:23:25,098
Mrs. Joyce, our senior sensitive...

1023
01:23:25,276 --> 01:23:28,074
...is doing a public reading tonight
if you're interested.

1024
01:23:28,245 --> 01:23:29,974
In the lecture hall.

1025
01:23:30,347 --> 01:23:33,180
MAN 3:
All right. I'll try my luck. Thank you.

1026
01:23:34,685 --> 01:23:36,016
Can I help you?

1027
01:23:36,520 --> 01:23:37,987
Oh, no, thanks.

1028
01:23:40,925 --> 01:23:43,485
I'm getting a strong feeling
over this side of the room.

1029
01:23:45,029 --> 01:23:47,725
Someone whose name starts with a "J."

1030
01:23:50,401 --> 01:23:53,268
Does the letter "J" mean anything
to anyone? Anyone?

1031
01:23:53,437 --> 01:23:55,132
Anyone?

1032
01:23:55,639 --> 01:23:56,867
Oh.

1033
01:23:57,308 --> 01:23:59,003
Don't be shy.

1034
01:23:59,944 --> 01:24:01,809
Tell us your name, please.

1035
01:24:02,881 --> 01:24:04,007
Marcus.

1036
01:24:04,750 --> 01:24:08,242
Marcus. Marcus. Come on.

1037
01:24:08,420 --> 01:24:10,445
Come up here where I can see you.

1038
01:24:11,590 --> 01:24:12,955
Good boy.

1039
01:24:13,325 --> 01:24:17,955
There's a good boy, Marcus.
That's right. I'm not going to hurt you.

1040
01:24:19,231 --> 01:24:20,596
That's lovely.

1041
01:24:21,032 --> 01:24:25,128
Now, Marcus,
you've lost someone recently.

1042
01:24:26,104 --> 01:24:28,129
Was it someone very close to you?

1043
01:24:30,475 --> 01:24:33,808
He's telling me his name.
It's Joe, or Jack.

1044
01:24:34,546 --> 01:24:35,877
- Jason.
- Jason, that's it.

1045
01:24:36,047 --> 01:24:39,312
He was very close to you, wasn't he?
Was he part of your family?

1046
01:24:43,488 --> 01:24:45,046
Is it your dad?

1047
01:24:47,359 --> 01:24:50,692
Well, Daddy says please don't be sad...

1048
01:24:50,862 --> 01:24:53,729
...and to look after Mummy
for him, will you?

1049
01:24:53,899 --> 01:24:55,958
Will you do that for him?

1050
01:24:56,701 --> 01:25:00,159
Give Marcus a round of applause,
ladies and gentlemen.

1051
01:25:02,575 --> 01:25:04,475
Lovely boy.

1052
01:25:04,644 --> 01:25:07,135
MAN:
And as I go into a trance...

1053
01:25:07,980 --> 01:25:11,780
...my spirit guide will speak to you
through me.

1054
01:25:12,785 --> 01:25:14,116
[SIGHS]

1055
01:25:15,221 --> 01:25:16,552
Oh.

1056
01:25:18,991 --> 01:25:21,858
[IN GRUFF VOICE]
Who summons me from the spirit world?

1057
01:25:23,229 --> 01:25:24,355
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Say your name.

1058
01:25:24,897 --> 01:25:27,195
- Marcus.
- Marcus.

1059
01:25:27,366 --> 01:25:32,531
[IN GRUFF VOICE]
Welcome, Marcus. My name is Yoshi.

1060
01:25:33,973 --> 01:25:37,238
What I'm doing is I'm adjusting
the level of the microphones.

1061
01:25:37,410 --> 01:25:39,002
Do you do physics at school?

1062
01:25:39,178 --> 01:25:42,306
Good. Then you know that all matter
vibrates at different speeds.

1063
01:25:42,481 --> 01:25:46,008
But in the spirit world,
operates at far higher levels.

1064
01:25:46,185 --> 01:25:48,779
So we can't hear them.
Not with our normal hearing.

1065
01:25:48,955 --> 01:25:52,015
So, what we really need
is an omnidirectional...

1066
01:25:52,191 --> 01:25:54,989
...supercardioid condenser microphone.

1067
01:25:55,428 --> 01:25:57,020
Like this beauty.

1068
01:25:57,330 --> 01:26:01,061
Right. I think we are ready.

1069
01:26:03,871 --> 01:26:05,361
And....

1070
01:26:09,743 --> 01:26:13,076
Jason? Are you there?

1071
01:26:14,681 --> 01:26:19,880
Your brother, Marcus, is here.
Is there a message for him?

1072
01:26:22,623 --> 01:26:25,888
It was the ancient Greeks
who first discovered it.

1073
01:26:27,160 --> 01:26:29,560
"Psychomanteum," they called it.

1074
01:26:29,730 --> 01:26:33,222
The reflective surface
being the conduit to the afterlife.

1075
01:26:33,400 --> 01:26:36,301
Nowadays, we call it "mirror gazing."

1076
01:26:36,470 --> 01:26:39,803
You might not be able to speak to him,
but you will see him...

1077
01:26:39,973 --> 01:26:42,168
...if you really want to, that is.

1078
01:26:44,111 --> 01:26:45,578
Did you see him?

1079
01:26:45,746 --> 01:26:47,077
No.

1080
01:26:48,982 --> 01:26:51,507
[PHONE RINGING]

1081
01:26:51,685 --> 01:26:53,585
Hello. Clare speaking.

1082
01:26:53,754 --> 01:26:56,052
There's no sign of him.
I'm gonna call the police.

1083
01:26:56,223 --> 01:26:59,090
CLARE: But that will not help.
- Well, I don't care what--

1084
01:26:59,726 --> 01:27:02,889
Hang on. He's here.
I'll call you right back.

1085
01:27:06,100 --> 01:27:07,727
I'm sorry.

1086
01:27:07,902 --> 01:27:09,199
DENNIS:
Ah--

1087
01:27:09,971 --> 01:27:11,598
Leave him be.

1088
01:28:20,142 --> 01:28:21,166
MAN:
Watch out!

1089
01:28:30,319 --> 01:28:31,752
WOMAN:
Excuse me.

1090
01:29:01,617 --> 01:29:03,608
[PEOPLE SCREAM]

1091
01:29:13,063 --> 01:29:15,054
[SIRENS WAILING IN DISTANCE]

1092
01:29:48,965 --> 01:29:50,796
SECRETARY [IN FRENCH]:
Sorry, we are running a little late.

1093
01:29:50,967 --> 01:29:52,025
Come in.

1094
01:29:52,202 --> 01:29:55,103
Everyone is upset by the events.

1095
01:29:59,542 --> 01:30:00,736
Sit down.

1096
01:30:03,948 --> 01:30:06,712
Marie, to be honest with you,
I'm a bit confused.

1097
01:30:07,718 --> 01:30:09,777
I thought we commissioned a book
about Francois Mitterrand.

1098
01:30:09,954 --> 01:30:12,548
Instead, you give us
the first three chapters of...

1099
01:30:12,723 --> 01:30:13,781
...Hereafter:

1100
01:30:15,359 --> 01:30:17,122
The Conspiracy of Silence.

1101
01:30:17,294 --> 01:30:20,855
[IN FRENCH] I realize it's not
what you were expecting.

1102
01:30:21,465 --> 01:30:24,400
You always said there weren't
enough surprises in publishing.

1103
01:30:24,568 --> 01:30:26,695
Well, this is certainly a surprise!

1104
01:30:32,343 --> 01:30:34,538
I don't know where to begin.

1105
01:30:34,712 --> 01:30:36,202
Did you at least find it interesting?

1106
01:30:36,380 --> 01:30:40,180
Of course.
You've always had a nose for a good story.

1107
01:30:40,351 --> 01:30:42,148
But we're a political publisher--

1108
01:30:42,319 --> 01:30:43,547
This is political!

1109
01:30:43,721 --> 01:30:47,919
This kind of material, however fascinating,
is for a specialized market.

1110
01:30:48,092 --> 01:30:51,152
JASMINE [ON TV]: This morning, in London,
six bombs went off in the heart of the city.

1111
01:30:51,328 --> 01:30:55,731
Apparently coordinated, the bombs
exploded at the height of the rush hour.

1112
01:30:59,970 --> 01:31:01,767
Why are you all against this?

1113
01:31:09,047 --> 01:31:11,345
Why are you so afraid of this?

1114
01:31:11,883 --> 01:31:13,248
This is real!

1115
01:31:13,418 --> 01:31:14,442
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1116
01:31:14,619 --> 01:31:16,450
This is scientific evidence...

1117
01:31:16,621 --> 01:31:19,613
...from well-known researchers
forced to work in secret.

1118
01:31:20,692 --> 01:31:24,788
A Nobel Prize winner, hounded
by the religious lobby. That's a story!

1119
01:31:25,897 --> 01:31:29,060
Better than a philandering,
dishonest old politician.

1120
01:31:29,234 --> 01:31:33,034
But a book like that would probably
have to be written in English...

1121
01:31:33,205 --> 01:31:34,934
...for the American market.

1122
01:31:36,074 --> 01:31:37,871
It happened to me, Michel.

1123
01:31:39,744 --> 01:31:41,609
I saw it with my own eyes.

1124
01:31:42,948 --> 01:31:44,438
Where we're going.

1125
01:31:46,418 --> 01:31:48,147
What we'll experience.

1126
01:31:49,821 --> 01:31:51,914
Each and every one of us.

1127
01:31:54,159 --> 01:31:55,820
That doesn't interest you?

1128
01:32:00,065 --> 01:32:03,557
Now listen, we commissioned a book
about Francois Mitterrand.

1129
01:32:04,103 --> 01:32:06,628
Either we agree on this
and you start writing it...

1130
01:32:06,806 --> 01:32:09,604
...or else I want my money back.
That's all I can say.

1131
01:32:33,432 --> 01:32:35,059
It was so humiliating.

1132
01:32:36,702 --> 01:32:39,330
They looked at me as if I'd lost my mind.

1133
01:32:39,505 --> 01:32:42,303
Six months ago they begged me
to write about anything.

1134
01:32:43,175 --> 01:32:45,609
Anything by the great Marie Lelay.

1135
01:32:47,380 --> 01:32:51,009
You'd better give me my job back.
I've had enough with being humiliated.

1136
01:32:54,720 --> 01:32:56,711
Today, they even took down my posters.

1137
01:32:57,323 --> 01:32:58,654
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1138
01:33:00,226 --> 01:33:01,523
Why didn't you tell me?

1139
01:33:03,830 --> 01:33:05,092
And your book?

1140
01:33:07,100 --> 01:33:10,695
I'll finish it in my spare time.
It's caused me enough trouble as it is.

1141
01:33:14,041 --> 01:33:15,201
What's the matter?

1142
01:33:16,376 --> 01:33:17,604
Look...

1143
01:33:18,245 --> 01:33:20,509
...getting your job back...

1144
01:33:20,681 --> 01:33:22,876
...might not be as easy as you think.

1145
01:33:23,817 --> 01:33:24,875
Why?

1146
01:33:25,552 --> 01:33:27,850
It was a temporary break.
And on your advice.

1147
01:33:28,622 --> 01:33:29,714
I know, but--

1148
01:33:30,724 --> 01:33:32,419
What we couldn't have foreseen is...

1149
01:33:32,592 --> 01:33:35,561
...you'd be talking in public
about these experiences.

1150
01:33:35,729 --> 01:33:39,995
- That you'd lose your credibility.
- But I didn't want to write this book!

1151
01:33:40,167 --> 01:33:41,725
It was your idea!

1152
01:33:41,902 --> 01:33:44,370
It was my idea you should write
about Mitterrand.

1153
01:33:45,405 --> 01:33:47,236
So, what are you saying?

1154
01:33:48,542 --> 01:33:51,067
I'm saying take some more time.

1155
01:33:51,244 --> 01:33:54,270
Finish the book, get it out
of your system, then come back.

1156
01:33:55,282 --> 01:33:57,580
It's that girl, isn't it?
My replacement?

1157
01:33:59,286 --> 01:34:01,220
I've watched her a few times.
She's good.

1158
01:34:01,688 --> 01:34:04,213
Yes, she is.
But not as good as you.

1159
01:34:05,927 --> 01:34:07,451
You're sleeping with her?

1160
01:34:08,896 --> 01:34:10,659
How can you say such a thing?

1161
01:34:13,434 --> 01:34:15,959
You always told me to ask
the tough questions.

1162
01:34:29,951 --> 01:34:31,282
[SIGHS]

1163
01:34:33,488 --> 01:34:34,819
It's funny....

1164
01:34:36,457 --> 01:34:38,084
Who'd have thought it?

1165
01:34:40,561 --> 01:34:42,426
A few months ago I was famous.

1166
01:34:43,297 --> 01:34:44,787
Rich.

1167
01:34:46,334 --> 01:34:47,801
A success story.

1168
01:34:50,138 --> 01:34:51,605
I was happy.

1169
01:34:53,241 --> 01:34:55,402
Fulfilled by my work.

1170
01:34:56,944 --> 01:34:58,411
By you.

1171
01:35:13,462 --> 01:35:16,954
All this happened because
you didn't buy your kids their gifts.

1172
01:35:17,132 --> 01:35:18,565
Because of what?

1173
01:35:18,734 --> 01:35:21,328
What are you talking about?
I don't understand.

1174
01:35:23,005 --> 01:35:24,632
Forget it. It doesn't matter.

1175
01:35:25,808 --> 01:35:27,139
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1176
01:35:39,688 --> 01:35:41,679
[PHONE RINGING]

1177
01:35:42,991 --> 01:35:44,982
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

1178
01:35:45,694 --> 01:35:47,127
[MICHEL SPEAKS IN FRENCH
OVER PHONE]

1179
01:35:49,965 --> 01:35:50,989
MICHEL [OVER PHONE]:
It's Michel.

1180
01:35:52,668 --> 01:35:53,828
Listen....

1181
01:35:55,337 --> 01:35:58,067
I feel terrible about our meeting
earlier today.

1182
01:35:59,708 --> 01:36:02,404
This book is obviously
very important to you.

1183
01:36:04,046 --> 01:36:07,573
I think everyone was a bit on edge
because of the events in London.

1184
01:36:09,819 --> 01:36:14,654
But I made a few calls. There are
two publishers who might be interested.

1185
01:36:15,325 --> 01:36:17,293
One American, one English.

1186
01:36:18,328 --> 01:36:19,488
Do you have a pen?

1187
01:36:19,696 --> 01:36:21,687
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

1188
01:36:27,303 --> 01:36:28,736
I'm listening.

1189
01:36:33,076 --> 01:36:34,407
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

1190
01:36:45,388 --> 01:36:47,379
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

1191
01:36:50,693 --> 01:36:53,924
BILLY: Anyways, I thought this would be
a good group reading room.

1192
01:36:54,097 --> 01:36:55,121
Group reading?

1193
01:36:55,298 --> 01:36:57,766
Yeah, where you could
read more people at once.

1194
01:36:57,934 --> 01:37:01,301
Up to 20 people or more, it's up to you.
They'd pay lower rates that way.

1195
01:37:01,471 --> 01:37:03,530
This would be your personal
consulting room.

1196
01:37:03,706 --> 01:37:07,972
And right next door, George,
this is gonna be my room.

1197
01:37:08,145 --> 01:37:10,579
I'm gonna make sure
everything gets taken care of.

1198
01:37:10,748 --> 01:37:12,215
You won't have to worry.

1199
01:37:12,750 --> 01:37:15,241
I don't understand.
What about your other businesses?

1200
01:37:15,419 --> 01:37:17,148
Oh, yeah, of course. They're gone.

1201
01:37:17,321 --> 01:37:19,448
Once this thing takes off,
forget it, you know?

1202
01:37:19,623 --> 01:37:22,490
Let's get you home. You need rest.
You got a big day tomorrow.

1203
01:37:22,660 --> 01:37:24,560
You already have three appointments.

1204
01:37:24,728 --> 01:37:26,059
- All right?
- Yeah.

1205
01:37:26,230 --> 01:37:27,595
BILLY:
Come on.

1206
01:37:47,751 --> 01:37:48,945
[DOORBELL RINGS]

1207
01:37:53,991 --> 01:37:56,323
- You Billy Lonegan?
- Yes.

1208
01:37:56,493 --> 01:37:58,620
Before he went, your brother
asked me to give this to you.

1209
01:37:58,796 --> 01:38:00,286
Went? Went where?

1210
01:38:00,464 --> 01:38:01,931
I have no idea.

1211
01:38:08,440 --> 01:38:09,702
GEORGE:
Dear Billy...

1212
01:38:10,175 --> 01:38:11,472
...I'm sorry.

1213
01:38:11,643 --> 01:38:14,737
I guess there's nothing I'll ever
be able to say to persuade you...

1214
01:38:14,913 --> 01:38:17,438
...that what I have isn't a gift,
but a curse.

1215
01:38:18,149 --> 01:38:21,346
I know you feel what I have
comes with a duty to help others.

1216
01:38:21,519 --> 01:38:24,955
But right now, the person
I most need to help is myself.

1217
01:38:25,123 --> 01:38:27,557
So I've decided to take some time out.

1218
01:38:27,726 --> 01:38:30,661
I don't know what the future will bring
or when I'll be back.

1219
01:38:30,829 --> 01:38:33,320
So don't wait up, so to speak.

1220
01:38:33,498 --> 01:38:37,332
Love to Jenni and the kids.
Your baby brother, George.

1221
01:38:51,883 --> 01:38:54,818
You know the recovery rate
in substance abuse cases like this.

1222
01:38:55,387 --> 01:38:57,582
- Yeah.
- Yeah. Very low.

1223
01:38:58,556 --> 01:39:01,889
So, what's the best way forward?
Are you okay for a little bit longer?

1224
01:39:03,495 --> 01:39:06,953
Yes. But not too long, please.

1225
01:39:07,133 --> 01:39:10,591
We're running out of ideas,
and it's beginning to take its toll.

1226
01:39:11,103 --> 01:39:13,435
Taking him to see
our previous child, Ricky.

1227
01:39:15,474 --> 01:39:18,272
Who knows, you know?
One kid talking to another.

1228
01:39:30,988 --> 01:39:32,717
MAN: Marie Lelay?
MARIE [IN ENGLISH]: Yes?

1229
01:39:32,890 --> 01:39:37,088
MAN: This is Richard Aronson
of Aquarius Books in Santa Fe, New Mexico.

1230
01:39:37,261 --> 01:39:38,558
MARIE:
Excuse me?

1231
01:39:38,730 --> 01:39:42,427
MAN: Aquarius books in Santa Fe?
A few months ago, you sent us your book.

1232
01:39:42,600 --> 01:39:44,693
I'm just ringing to say
how much we liked it.

1233
01:39:44,869 --> 01:39:48,202
Sorry it's taken so long, but we loved it,
and we'd like to publish it.

1234
01:39:48,373 --> 01:39:50,500
MARIE: Really?
MAN: In fact, we'd like to print it...

1235
01:39:50,675 --> 01:39:53,644
...in time for a book fair in London
in the spring.

1236
01:39:53,811 --> 01:39:55,938
- You're based in Paris?
MARIE: Yes.

1237
01:39:56,114 --> 01:39:59,447
MAN: So, if we were to ask,
going to London wouldn't be inconvenient?

1238
01:39:59,617 --> 01:40:01,585
MARIE:
No. No, no, no, not at all.

1239
01:40:01,753 --> 01:40:04,244
MAN: That would be a good opportunity
to do some publicity.

1240
01:40:04,422 --> 01:40:07,391
Maybe a reading. It's an incredible story.

1241
01:40:07,559 --> 01:40:09,322
MARIE:
Thank you.

1242
01:40:15,134 --> 01:40:16,897
TOUR GUIDE:
And here we are.

1243
01:40:18,837 --> 01:40:21,328
48 Doughty Street.

1244
01:40:21,540 --> 01:40:23,269
Charles Dickens' home in London...

1245
01:40:23,442 --> 01:40:27,310
...where he lived with his wife Catherine
and their children.

1246
01:40:27,479 --> 01:40:30,107
Anyone know how many children?

1247
01:40:30,282 --> 01:40:31,647
[TOURISTS MURMURING INDISTINCTLY]

1248
01:40:31,817 --> 01:40:33,978
Here we are in the main hallway.

1249
01:40:34,153 --> 01:40:36,621
- This is the view that greeted the author...
- Ten.

1250
01:40:36,789 --> 01:40:38,484
...as he walked in each time.

1251
01:40:38,657 --> 01:40:41,455
Everything has been preserved
exactly as it was.

1252
01:40:41,627 --> 01:40:45,825
So just follow me up the stairs.
We'll start at the top of the house.

1253
01:40:49,201 --> 01:40:51,692
Now we move in to Dickens' study.

1254
01:40:51,870 --> 01:40:55,772
And directly in front of you, you'll see
an original copy of A Christmas Carol...

1255
01:40:55,941 --> 01:40:59,138
...arguably one of Dickens'
most famous books.

1256
01:40:59,645 --> 01:41:02,773
But over here, the thing I expect
most of you have come to see.

1257
01:41:02,948 --> 01:41:05,143
Dickens' desk,
where he wrote most of his books.

1258
01:41:05,952 --> 01:41:10,514
On this wall we have several illustrations
for The Mystery of Edwin Drood...

1259
01:41:10,690 --> 01:41:13,716
...the novel Dickens was writing
at the time of his death.

1260
01:41:14,527 --> 01:41:18,395
And on the far wall here,
a painting loved by Dickens fans.

1261
01:41:18,598 --> 01:41:21,032
It shows the author asleep at his desk...

1262
01:41:21,201 --> 01:41:24,295
...with characters from his novels
floating in the air around him.

1263
01:41:25,638 --> 01:41:27,936
Anyone know its name?

1264
01:41:28,107 --> 01:41:29,802
Dickens' Dream.

1265
01:41:29,976 --> 01:41:33,139
TOUR GUIDE:
It's called Dickens' Dream.

1266
01:41:36,483 --> 01:41:37,745
This way, please.

1267
01:41:40,053 --> 01:41:43,511
Just gather again at the front
of the building.

1268
01:41:49,696 --> 01:41:51,664
Does anyone have any questions?

1269
01:41:57,136 --> 01:41:58,933
GEORGE:
What is the date today?

1270
01:41:59,138 --> 01:42:02,471
TOUR GUIDE: Fourteenth.
-It is the 14th. Yeah, okay.

1271
01:42:05,880 --> 01:42:07,905
I think you'll like Ricky.

1272
01:42:08,082 --> 01:42:11,779
He was about your age when he first
came to us, and just as shy.

1273
01:42:12,353 --> 01:42:16,687
Now he's a grown man.
With a job and his own flat.

1274
01:42:21,028 --> 01:42:23,792
DENNIS: He's in here somewhere.
ANGELA: He said he'd meet us at the front.

1275
01:42:23,964 --> 01:42:25,795
DENNIS:
Where is he?

1276
01:42:25,966 --> 01:42:28,799
ANGELA: Where is he?
DENNIS: Hey. Look at this.

1277
01:42:28,969 --> 01:42:30,698
- Hey.
RICKY: Heh, heh, heh.

1278
01:42:33,674 --> 01:42:36,108
Oh, my God, I hardly recognized you.

1279
01:42:36,277 --> 01:42:39,075
- You gonna arrest us?
- Yeah. Not if you behave yourself.

1280
01:42:39,246 --> 01:42:41,305
Marcus, this is Ricky.

1281
01:42:41,482 --> 01:42:43,211
RICKY:
You all right, mate?

1282
01:42:43,384 --> 01:42:44,544
Fancy a coffee first?

1283
01:42:44,718 --> 01:42:46,845
- Yeah, that's a great idea.
- Yeah, great idea.

1284
01:42:47,821 --> 01:42:49,789
It's an amazing place, isn't it?

1285
01:42:49,957 --> 01:42:51,254
Can I have a look around?

1286
01:42:52,927 --> 01:42:55,794
Yeah. But meet us back here
in one hour, yeah?

1287
01:42:56,297 --> 01:42:58,060
- Good lad.
- Okay?

1288
01:43:01,402 --> 01:43:04,803
It's been nearly a year.
He hardly speaks to us.

1289
01:43:05,005 --> 01:43:06,563
Neither did I, remember?

1290
01:43:06,741 --> 01:43:09,574
This one's different. He's not like you.

1291
01:43:10,579 --> 01:43:12,479
RICKY: Let's have that coffee, yeah?
- Yeah.

1292
01:43:12,647 --> 01:43:14,410
RICKY:
Oh, lovely.

1293
01:43:15,250 --> 01:43:17,241
[CHATTERING]

1294
01:43:28,029 --> 01:43:32,966
MAN [OVER MICROPHONE]: "'She is,
I do assure you, the winegariest person.'

1295
01:43:33,768 --> 01:43:38,262
Mr. Plornish, with a modest
disavowal of his merits...

1296
01:43:38,440 --> 01:43:41,170
...opened the room door
for her readmission...

1297
01:43:41,343 --> 01:43:44,779
...and followed her in with such
an exceedingly bald presence...

1298
01:43:44,946 --> 01:43:47,005
...of not having been out at all...

1299
01:43:47,182 --> 01:43:51,050
...that her father might have observed it
without being very suspicious.

1300
01:43:51,252 --> 01:43:55,712
In his affable unconsciousness,
however, he took no heed.

1301
01:43:55,890 --> 01:43:59,986
Plornish, after the little conversation,
took his leave.

1302
01:44:00,161 --> 01:44:02,493
Making the tour of the prison
before he left...

1303
01:44:02,664 --> 01:44:05,497
...and looking on at a game of skittles...

1304
01:44:05,668 --> 01:44:08,034
...with the mixed feelings
of an old inhabitant...

1305
01:44:08,204 --> 01:44:11,401
...who had his private reasons
for believing...

1306
01:44:11,574 --> 01:44:16,876
...that it might be his destiny
to come back again."

1307
01:44:20,282 --> 01:44:21,909
Thank you.

1308
01:44:23,352 --> 01:44:24,683
Thank you.

1309
01:44:24,854 --> 01:44:29,518
Now, if any of you wish to purchase a CD,
I am at your disposal.

1310
01:44:29,692 --> 01:44:31,683
- Thank you.
JACOBI: Thank you.

1311
01:44:31,861 --> 01:44:33,522
- Hello.
- Hi. George.

1312
01:44:33,696 --> 01:44:35,254
- To George.
- Yeah. George Lonegan.

1313
01:44:35,431 --> 01:44:36,625
To George.

1314
01:44:36,799 --> 01:44:40,098
I'm a-- It's-- This is an honor, Mr. Jacobi.

1315
01:44:40,269 --> 01:44:42,897
I'm a really big fan. You have no idea.

1316
01:44:43,072 --> 01:44:45,063
Thank you.
You're a long way from home.

1317
01:44:45,241 --> 01:44:47,038
- Yes.
- Yes.

1318
01:44:48,177 --> 01:44:50,941
- Did you enjoy it?
- Very much, yes.

1319
01:44:53,449 --> 01:44:56,111
- There you are. Thank you.
- Thank you so much. Thank you.

1320
01:44:56,318 --> 01:44:58,252
- Good luck.
- Thank you.

1321
01:45:01,190 --> 01:45:03,556
MARIE [OVER MICROPHONE]:
"I felt connected to another world...

1322
01:45:03,726 --> 01:45:07,457
...a place of utter peace and tranquility.

1323
01:45:09,099 --> 01:45:13,195
Whether what I saw was a genuine
glimpse of the afterlife...

1324
01:45:13,370 --> 01:45:16,806
...or just a concussed fantasy,
I'll probably never know.

1325
01:45:17,574 --> 01:45:22,443
I arrive at the end of my journey
with as many question as I started with.

1326
01:45:27,084 --> 01:45:30,212
I certainly never imagined
I would be exposed...

1327
01:45:30,387 --> 01:45:33,754
...to that kind of prejudice
and close-mindedness.

1328
01:45:33,924 --> 01:45:36,916
We obviously still have
a long way to go...

1329
01:45:37,094 --> 01:45:41,224
...before we will be able to deal
with death and what follows...

1330
01:45:41,398 --> 01:45:44,492
...in anything approaching
a sensible fashion."

1331
01:45:47,804 --> 01:45:52,468
Okay, so if you want to buy my book,
I can sign it.

1332
01:45:52,642 --> 01:45:54,371
You're welcome. Thank you.

1333
01:45:54,544 --> 01:45:56,535
[CROWD CLAPPING]

1334
01:46:02,119 --> 01:46:03,643
- Hello. What's your name?
MARIA: Hello.

1335
01:46:03,820 --> 01:46:05,720
- Maria.
- Maria.

1336
01:46:11,763 --> 01:46:14,129
- Thank you, Maria.
- Thank you very much.

1337
01:46:14,298 --> 01:46:16,732
MICHAEL: Michael.
- Michael. Okay.

1338
01:46:23,407 --> 01:46:24,806
Thank you.

1339
01:46:24,976 --> 01:46:26,944
Honora.

1340
01:46:31,082 --> 01:46:32,606
MARIE: Thank you.
- Thank you.

1341
01:46:32,784 --> 01:46:35,514
- My name's George.
- George.

1342
01:46:46,230 --> 01:46:47,561
[WHOOSH]

1343
01:46:56,240 --> 01:46:57,707
WOMAN: To Penny.
- Sorry?

1344
01:46:57,875 --> 01:46:59,240
- Penny.
- Penny.

1345
01:47:05,316 --> 01:47:08,808
MARCUS:
Wait a minute. I recognize you.

1346
01:47:08,987 --> 01:47:10,147
Sorry?

1347
01:47:10,322 --> 01:47:12,017
You're that psychic.

1348
01:47:13,759 --> 01:47:16,887
No, no. Um.... No, you got me mistaken
with someone else.

1349
01:47:17,062 --> 01:47:19,030
Yes, you are. You're George Lonegan.

1350
01:47:19,198 --> 01:47:23,032
- I don't even know who that is. No, I'm not.
- You are George Lonegan.

1351
01:47:23,769 --> 01:47:25,464
- You got me--
- I need to talk to you.

1352
01:47:25,637 --> 01:47:28,367
No, you got me mixed up
with someone else.

1353
01:47:28,540 --> 01:47:30,872
Please, I need to talk to you.
You're a psychic.

1354
01:47:31,043 --> 01:47:32,806
I'm not. I'm not who you think I am.

1355
01:47:32,978 --> 01:47:36,414
I saw it on the Internet.
You are a psychic.

1356
01:47:37,115 --> 01:47:39,413
What? What is it? What do you want?

1357
01:47:39,585 --> 01:47:42,645
If it's a reading, I have news for you.
I don't do it anymore.

1358
01:47:42,821 --> 01:47:44,914
Now leave me alone.

1359
01:47:48,927 --> 01:47:51,828
MAN [OVER MICROPHONE]:
"When I look back on this, it was insane.

1360
01:47:51,997 --> 01:47:55,296
The rudder cables became useless
and I lost my ability to steer.

1361
01:47:55,500 --> 01:47:59,095
I was helpless amid the swirling
maritime mass of industry.

1362
01:47:59,271 --> 01:48:01,899
The sea had turned malevolently dark.

1363
01:48:02,074 --> 01:48:06,374
What had once seemed friendly was now
a violent monster trying to kill me."

1364
01:48:07,113 --> 01:48:10,241
Did you see a Frenchwoman who was
here just a few minutes ago?

1365
01:48:10,416 --> 01:48:12,748
She's gone. She left already.

1366
01:48:14,387 --> 01:48:15,877
MAN:
"You realize you're in danger...

1367
01:48:16,055 --> 01:48:19,218
...and dwell on how things might end.
I spent every second...."

1368
01:49:17,618 --> 01:49:19,779
CLERK: Hi, can I help you?
- I'm looking for someone.

1369
01:49:19,954 --> 01:49:21,717
CLERK:
Come on, please. Move along.

1370
01:49:39,807 --> 01:49:41,798
[CROWD CHEERING ON TV]

1371
01:49:44,878 --> 01:49:47,346
MAN [ON TV]: Hill cuts it back nicely,
perhaps almost too far.

1372
01:49:47,681 --> 01:49:50,673
But it's gone in! It's gone in!

1373
01:49:50,851 --> 01:49:53,217
Andy Fisher!

1374
01:49:53,387 --> 01:49:55,947
You have to question that play....

1375
01:50:09,437 --> 01:50:10,995
GEORGE:
Okay.

1376
01:50:12,474 --> 01:50:14,339
We better get you inside.

1377
01:50:17,479 --> 01:50:19,140
Come on.

1378
01:50:22,751 --> 01:50:25,083
- What's your name?
- Marcus.

1379
01:50:36,097 --> 01:50:40,932
Okay. Couple of ground rules
before we get started.

1380
01:50:41,736 --> 01:50:43,135
I'm sorry about the woman.

1381
01:50:43,304 --> 01:50:44,430
What woman?

1382
01:50:44,606 --> 01:50:46,574
The woman at the book fair.

1383
01:50:47,709 --> 01:50:49,734
I could tell you liked her.

1384
01:50:50,211 --> 01:50:51,269
No, I didn't.

1385
01:50:51,446 --> 01:50:54,415
Yes, you did.
So I'm sorry for taking you away.

1386
01:50:54,582 --> 01:50:58,985
I don't have any idea what you're
talking about. Here, sit down.

1387
01:51:00,655 --> 01:51:02,122
Okay.

1388
01:51:03,158 --> 01:51:04,591
Let's do this.

1389
01:51:05,560 --> 01:51:08,393
Okay, I'm gonna grab your hands
because it seems to help...

1390
01:51:08,564 --> 01:51:10,191
...and then I'll let go.

1391
01:51:11,534 --> 01:51:15,095
Don't worry, I'm not gonna go into
any stupid trance or anything like that.

1392
01:51:15,271 --> 01:51:18,934
I just gotta grab them to get a connection,
then I'll let go. Okay?

1393
01:51:19,108 --> 01:51:22,566
Now, I want you to answer yes or no
to everything I ask.

1394
01:51:22,745 --> 01:51:24,975
- You understand?
- Yes.

1395
01:51:25,147 --> 01:51:26,705
Okay.

1396
01:51:27,817 --> 01:51:29,580
Let's see them.

1397
01:51:35,491 --> 01:51:36,515
[WHOOSH]

1398
01:51:42,998 --> 01:51:44,022
Okay.

1399
01:51:46,635 --> 01:51:49,160
Okay, someone close to you
has passed away?

1400
01:51:49,805 --> 01:51:51,136
Yes.

1401
01:51:51,941 --> 01:51:52,965
A male?

1402
01:51:54,710 --> 01:51:56,200
Yes.

1403
01:51:56,645 --> 01:51:59,113
He was young when he died.

1404
01:51:59,281 --> 01:52:00,805
Yes.

1405
01:52:01,717 --> 01:52:03,776
This person your brother?

1406
01:52:08,391 --> 01:52:10,188
Older brother.

1407
01:52:13,497 --> 01:52:15,795
But not by much, he says.

1408
01:52:17,534 --> 01:52:19,627
Only by a few minutes.

1409
01:52:22,372 --> 01:52:24,169
I'm sorry, kid.

1410
01:52:27,377 --> 01:52:31,939
I gotta concentrate.
This guy.... This guy talks a lot.

1411
01:52:32,115 --> 01:52:34,049
Talks fast.

1412
01:52:34,217 --> 01:52:36,447
Got a really weird laugh.

1413
01:52:37,387 --> 01:52:40,083
Okay. Ahem. He says...

1414
01:52:40,757 --> 01:52:43,487
...there's so much he wants to tell you.

1415
01:52:44,828 --> 01:52:46,921
You wouldn't believe how it is.

1416
01:52:47,397 --> 01:52:49,865
How you can be all things...

1417
01:52:51,168 --> 01:52:52,931
...and all at once.

1418
01:52:54,938 --> 01:52:56,701
And the weightlessness.

1419
01:52:57,174 --> 01:52:59,233
He says that's cool.

1420
01:53:00,243 --> 01:53:01,767
Now he's laughing.

1421
01:53:03,647 --> 01:53:05,410
He's got a funny laugh.

1422
01:53:05,682 --> 01:53:07,206
Um....

1423
01:53:08,085 --> 01:53:09,518
Okay.

1424
01:53:12,757 --> 01:53:16,022
He says how you
always looked up to him...

1425
01:53:16,661 --> 01:53:20,495
...and relied on him
to make the decision...

1426
01:53:21,199 --> 01:53:23,895
...how maybe you used that
as an excuse.

1427
01:53:25,069 --> 01:53:26,696
Is that true?

1428
01:53:27,672 --> 01:53:30,470
Okay. He says can't do that anymore.

1429
01:53:33,044 --> 01:53:34,705
Now you're on your own.

1430
01:53:36,614 --> 01:53:40,311
Okay, now, hang on, okay, now.
Now he's saying something about a hat.

1431
01:53:41,185 --> 01:53:42,812
The cap?

1432
01:53:42,987 --> 01:53:45,285
A cap. Okay.

1433
01:53:48,392 --> 01:53:52,260
He says to take it off right now.
Take it off.

1434
01:53:54,465 --> 01:53:57,263
He doesn't--
He's telling you not to wear it again...

1435
01:53:58,769 --> 01:54:00,760
...because it was his.

1436
01:54:02,106 --> 01:54:05,405
And that's why he knocked it off
your head that day?

1437
01:54:07,111 --> 01:54:10,137
At the tube? Do you know
what he's talking about?

1438
01:54:12,184 --> 01:54:13,617
Okay.

1439
01:54:14,486 --> 01:54:18,149
He says good thing he did too.

1440
01:54:24,229 --> 01:54:27,357
And that's the last time
he's ever looking out for you.

1441
01:54:29,234 --> 01:54:30,667
I'm sorry. I'm, uh....

1442
01:54:34,773 --> 01:54:39,107
I'm sorry, I'm losing him now.
He's leaving. He wants to leave.

1443
01:54:43,749 --> 01:54:45,273
No, Jase.

1444
01:54:46,351 --> 01:54:47,545
Don't go.

1445
01:54:48,487 --> 01:54:51,354
You can't. Don't leave me.

1446
01:54:51,523 --> 01:54:53,616
I don't wanna be here without you.

1447
01:54:54,660 --> 01:54:57,493
Please, Jase, don't go. I miss you.

1448
01:54:57,663 --> 01:55:01,360
Okay, he came back. He's here. He says...

1449
01:55:03,568 --> 01:55:07,834
...if you're worried about being
on your own, don't be.

1450
01:55:08,675 --> 01:55:09,903
You're not.

1451
01:55:10,176 --> 01:55:14,237
Because he is you and you are him.

1452
01:55:15,281 --> 01:55:16,839
One cell.

1453
01:55:17,183 --> 01:55:18,582
One person.

1454
01:55:20,186 --> 01:55:21,710
Always.

1455
01:55:22,689 --> 01:55:23,917
I miss you.

1456
01:55:24,824 --> 01:55:28,760
Please, Jase, don't go.
Please come back.

1457
01:55:28,928 --> 01:55:30,555
I miss you so badly.

1458
01:55:33,599 --> 01:55:37,433
Okay, wait. He's leaving again.
Hold on, hold on. I'm sorry.

1459
01:55:37,603 --> 01:55:38,900
Well, where's he gone?

1460
01:55:41,307 --> 01:55:43,673
I'm sorry, kid. I don't know.

1461
01:55:44,711 --> 01:55:46,872
But you've done all those readings.

1462
01:55:48,715 --> 01:55:50,444
I still don't know.

1463
01:55:52,018 --> 01:55:53,542
Sorry.

1464
01:56:02,128 --> 01:56:04,824
Okay. We better get you home.

1465
01:56:49,276 --> 01:56:51,267
[RINGING]

1466
01:56:54,381 --> 01:56:56,941
- Hello?
MARCUS [OVER PHONE]: May Fair.

1467
01:56:57,885 --> 01:56:58,909
What?

1468
01:56:59,319 --> 01:57:03,380
The hotel where she's staying.
The woman you like?

1469
01:57:04,825 --> 01:57:06,520
What are you talking about?

1470
01:57:06,693 --> 01:57:10,094
Well, I rang up the publisher
and said I heard her speak...

1471
01:57:10,265 --> 01:57:13,632
...wanted to drop off a letter
saying how interesting it was.

1472
01:57:13,802 --> 01:57:15,497
Anyway, that's the name.

1473
01:57:15,670 --> 01:57:16,830
May Fair.

1474
01:57:17,005 --> 01:57:20,771
Okay, well, that's really interesting,
but what does that have to do with me?

1475
01:57:20,942 --> 01:57:22,239
[LINE DISCONNECTS]

1476
01:57:22,410 --> 01:57:23,775
Hello?

1477
01:57:25,079 --> 01:57:26,410
[SIGHS]

1478
01:57:29,117 --> 01:57:30,948
Well, I'll be.

1479
01:57:42,831 --> 01:57:44,492
I must be crazy.

1480
01:57:46,434 --> 01:57:47,799
DOORMAN:
Morning, sir.

1481
01:57:52,040 --> 01:57:53,735
WOMAN 1:
Okay.

1482
01:57:53,975 --> 01:57:57,376
- Here's your room key. Enjoy your stay.
WOMAN 2: Thank you very much.

1483
01:58:00,081 --> 01:58:02,743
Hi. I'm looking for a guest. Marie Lelay?

1484
01:58:02,917 --> 01:58:05,147
Okay. Okay.

1485
01:58:10,960 --> 01:58:13,758
No, there's no answer from the room,
I'm afraid, sir.

1486
01:58:13,963 --> 01:58:16,056
Would you like to leave a message?

1487
01:58:17,533 --> 01:58:18,966
No.

1488
01:58:20,202 --> 01:58:23,831
Actually, you know what? I would, I would.
Do you have a pen and paper?

1489
01:58:24,006 --> 01:58:25,496
Sure.

1490
01:58:26,475 --> 01:58:29,035
- Pen, paper.
- Thank you.

1491
01:58:29,211 --> 01:58:31,008
CLERK:
You're welcome.

1492
01:59:43,086 --> 01:59:44,747
Thank you.

1493
01:59:48,158 --> 01:59:49,489
This is it.

1494
01:59:51,761 --> 01:59:54,321
Marcus? Good luck.

1495
02:00:03,707 --> 02:00:05,038
[SIGHS]

1496
02:00:18,990 --> 02:00:20,582
Come here.

1497
02:00:22,360 --> 02:00:23,987
I missed you so much.

1498
02:00:24,795 --> 02:00:26,194
Oh, Marcus.

1499
02:00:28,966 --> 02:00:31,867
Come here. I missed you so much.

1500
02:00:35,706 --> 02:00:37,697
[CHATTERING]

1501
02:01:51,683 --> 02:01:53,150
Marie?

1502
02:02:09,134 --> 02:02:11,602
- Hello.
- Hello.


